[{"sha":"e6a471199437e3e7ae53988495fd598238078619","author":{"name":"Katherine Wu","email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com"},"message":"Refactor SavedModel SaverDef implementation so that the save/restore functions are generated in the Eager context.

This change prepares the SavedModel code to allow users to register advanced checkpoint saving/restore functions.

The SaverDef is a SavedModel field that allows TF2 SavedModels to be compatible with TF1. Before this CL, the SaverDef is generated by copying all objects and resource tensors from the eager context/default graph to the SavedModel exported graph.

The object-copying will not work well when we start introducing custom objects and classes, so this change defines the save and restore functions in same context that the user is saving in.

The extra arguments in `GraphView.frozen_saveables` are removed, and there is a slight reshuffling of code to make things the functionality partitions clearer.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[MLIR][KernelGen] Fix GPU module cache and make it a kernel resource

This fixes a subtle bug in the GPU module caches, which assumed that no two GPU
modules are loaded from the same memory location. When JIT-compiling kernels,
however, this can (and did) happen, which previously lead to a false cache hit,
resulting in the use of an incorrect GPU kernel.

Making the GPU module cache a kernel resource binds its lifetime to that of the
kernel context and also to that of the JIT cache. In this way, we can again
guarantee the needed assumption for the lifetime of the caches. Unfortunately,
there is no cheap alternative to the module data pointer to use as a key for the
cache.
